<h2 id="cfp">Call for Papers (<a href="">source</a>, 0 taggings)</h2>
<h3>Invitation to COMLAN - Special Issue from SLE 2017</h3>
<p>
</p>
<p>Dear █████,
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>we invite you to submit a revised version of your <a href="../sle2017/index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper entitled "█████" to the Special Issue from <a href="../sle2017/index.html">SLE 2017</a> of the Elsevier Journal Computer Languages, Systems and Structures (COMLAN).
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>We would like for you to extend the paper with improvements you deem necessary for submission to the journal. The paper must be extended roughly by 30%. Do not submit just minor revisions or even the same paper. You can change the title of the paper to reflect changes. Please note that the paper will be reviewed according to the standards of the journal and that acceptance/rejection of the paper will be based upon those reviews as decided by the journal editors.
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>During submission, you have to compose a letter to the editors of the special issue:
</p>
<p>
</p>
<ul>
<li>1. Here you have to mention that this paper is a SPECIAL ISSUE PAPER FROM <a href="../sle2017/index.html">SLE 2017</a>.</li>
<li>2. Explain in a few items the major extensions that have been made in order to meet the "30% more content" target, and why are these changes relevant.</li>
</ul>
<p>
</p>
<p>Please submit the extended version by May 20, 2018. Please inform us by February 6, 2018 if you are accepting this offer.
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>Best regards,
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>Benoit Combemale, Bernhard Rumpe
</p>
<p>
</p>
<p>Special Issue Editors</p><h2 id="lop">List of Papers (2, <a href="https://dblp.org/db/journals/vlc/vlc50.html">source</a>)</h2>
<ul class="lop">

<li><em><a href="paper01.html">Software meta-language engineering and CBS</a></em> (<a href="../profile/PeterDMosses.html">Peter D. Mosses</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM" title="The paper is explicitly about engineering semantic meta-languages (culminating in CBS) for specifying software languages.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL" title="It focuses on behavioural/executable semantics via component-based semantics (funcons) and operational specification styles (e.g., MSOS/I-MSOS lineage).">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL" title="A core objective is reuse of semantic components (funcons) across languages to reduce duplication in specifications.">T1E: Reuse</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL" title="It emphasises co-evolution between a language and its formal specification, treating semantics engineering as an ongoing evolution/maintenance problem.">T2B: Evolution</span></a>
</li></ul></li>
<li><em><a href="paper02.html">FlowSpec: A declarative specification language for intra-procedural flow-Sensitive data-flow analysis</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JeffSmits.html">Jeff Smits</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a>) 
<ul><li>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM" title="FlowSpec is a DSL for specifying dataflow analyses over programming languages.">T3C: DSLs</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL" title="Dataflow analyses are classic static-semantics analyses, and the DSL is for declaring such analyses.">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title="It plays the role of a meta-language for describing analyses over language control-flow graphs.">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title="The work includes language-engineering infrastructure for defining CFGs and running the specified analyses.">T4A: Workbenches</span></a>
</li></ul></li></ul><h2 id="org">Organisers</h2><ul>
<li><a href="../profile/BenoîtCombemale.html">Benoît Combemale</a> (<a href="sle2017s/index.html">Editor</a>)</li>
<li><a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a> (<a href="sle2017s/index.html">Editor</a>)</li>
</ul>
